post_text: How fun does this sound!? Get out in Jennings and find Antoine the Alligator! Details below and on their event page!
shared_text:
Zigler Art MuseumBook Signing Event- Antoine & Friends
August 22 at 1:46 AM 路

It's time for An Alligator Hunt! Grab the family and head out to explore what our amazing town has to offer. We want to spend the entire week celebrating our hometown Author, Celia Joe Black, and Illustrator, Jessica Inez Trahan! So starting tomorrow, we are all on the hunt. Celia and Jessica will go live tomorrow at their first Book Singing event at The Steamer Trunk in Downtown Jennings, marking the start of our hunt! Then, your off to find Antoine, our book's main character. Look for him in the windows of businesses around town (there are 40 out there!!) and snap a pic! It can be a selfie, or for our camera shy fans, a thumbs up! We got really creative with our thumbs selfies, check them out below. Then you'll share your pic to this event page! Each Antoine you find gives you an entry in to our Grand Prize Drawing (worth over $150!!). So get ready. Set. Hunt!

post_text: Tracie worked for Jeff Davis Parish Economic Development and Tourism for over 16 years. When you work here, its more than a 9-5 job. We are a small, close knit office that spends a lot of time together. You really do become a work family. As many of you know, Tracie didnt know the word NO. She embraced every opportunity to help her community, either in a work capacity or personally. She was integral in every project, event, and function we planned and participated in. She kept all of us in line and on task. We have had so many wonderful times together, both in and out of the office. From handling gators, planning festivals and meetings, the Stearman Fly In each year, to the building of our new Gator Chateau, she did it all with gusto. We will miss her dearly and our office will certainly have a void with her being gone. We pray for all of her family and friends she has left behind that knew and loved her. Rest in Peace, our dear friend

Billy Nungesser Lt. Governor of Louisiana
April 30 at 1:21 PM 路

Happy Birthday, Louisiana! On this day in 1812, Louisiana was admitted into the Union as the 18th U.S. state. This happened exactly nine years after the Louisiana Purchase agreement was made and Louisiana was the first of thirteen states to be carved out from the territory and accepted into the United States.

There is so much to love about our great state including delicious food and cajun music! What are some of your favorite things that you can find in #OnlyLouisiana? Let me know in the comments below.

Hey its that time again. We here at Hobos, with Jeff LaBouve (Jeffs AC and Heating) and Paul Dupuis will be cooking again tomorrow night. But this time Michael Cassidy, Jennings Tractor and Equipment(Corey Cormier and Ellen Daigle Cormier), and Guillotte Brothers (Frank and Steve Guillotte) will be providing the meal. Its awesome that these 3 sponsors have stepped up to the plate to provide a plate of food for our health care members! They are providing meals for the Jennings American Legion Hospital, Jennings Police Department, Jeff Davis Parish Sheriffs Office, JenningsFire Department and anyone that works in a related field. (EMTs, First Responders, etc.)

We will be delivering meals to each place above starting at 5pm but we want to provide a meal to you if you are not working at said place. So please swing by Hobos and pick a meal up.

We are looking forward to serving you again!

Please share this post and tag people that work in the field above so we can provide a meal to them in this pandemic.

Louisiana Department of Wildlife and Fisheries
April 7 at 4:14 PM 路

Feeling trapped at home? We think its the perfect time fur some trapper education! (See that we did there? ) Through our FREE online workshop, you can learn about trapping basics, such as trap types and history, how to set traps and how to handle them safely. The course is designed to allow each student to work at their own pace and when it is most convenient for them. In addition, we will invite all online students to a fun and engaging hands-on trapping workshop in the fall. Create a free account here: https://conservationlearning.org/

post_text:
The Census Will Never Ask Certain Questions
During the 2020 Census, the Census Bureau will never ask you for:
Your Social Security number.
Money or donations.
Anything on behalf of a political party.
Your bank or credit card account numbers.
Additionally, there is no citizenship question on the 2020 Census.
If someone claiming to be from the Census Bureau contacts you via email or phone and asks you for one of these things, it's a scam, and you should not cooperate. For more information, visit Avoiding Fraud and Scams.
